metadata.title: Revisited

reviews.reviewbody:
Lehrer's second "Live" album "Tom Lehrer Revisited" was originally self-released on his Lehrer Records label (cat. # TL 101 - mono only). Side 1 was recorded in Cambridge, Mass. and side 2 was recorded in Australia.
The Australian recordings were not as well-recorded as the Cambridge tapes, with lesser sound quality (but equally superb performances.)  

In Australia, Decca did their own thing and issue a live LP "Tom Lehrer Discovers Australia (and vice versa)" pulled entirely from their recordings,

Decca in the UK did their own thing by issuing the entire Cambridge performance and not including any Australian recordings, citing them inferior.

This album was not re-issued in the US as part of Lehrer's 1960's contract with Reprise.  However, it did see first reissue on the "The Remains of Tom Lehrer" set from Rhino/Warner Bros. Decca in the UK kept the LP in print until the early 80's.

What Warner/Rhino did  for this reissue was euse the UK version of "Revisited" with the all-Cambridge recording.  As this is now considered the most "Common" version, the original Lehrer pressing is hard to come by. So now "Tom Lehrer Revisited" is truly REVISITED for the digital era.

reviews.reviewtitle: ALL P. D. —Please Post in FULL.
reviews.reviewbody:
Please read Dr. Lehrer's website for further information as to his unusual copyright status. 

https://tomlehrersongs.com/

Dr. Lehrer would like you to POST ALL OF HIE WORK IN FULL, —for GRATIS - FREE!    He does not expect, desire, nor seek payment of any sort.  Dr. Lehrer is 95 and has legally converted all his compositions to the PUBLIC DOMAIN.  He needs no money and would rather see his work distributed for FREE.
As Dr. Lehrer says on his website,

"In short, I no longer retain any rights to any of my songs.
So help yourselves, and don’t send me any money."

In the beginning, Dr. Lehrer signed NO contracts with any record labels. After seeking a record contract, he took a look at the one-sided, usury publishing contracts and wondered why he needed ANY record company to steal his money!   Dr. Lehrer  booked and paid for his own studio time.  He paid for mastering (i.e., lathing and the making of a mother and pressing stampers. ) He copyrighted his material and registered with ASCAP.  
Tom Lehrer's night club engagements quickly made him famous.  He became in such demand that he was paid more than any of his contemporary performers. He had NO management as he needed no management.  
Dr. Lehrer realised that his self-made records would sell without advertising or "distribution". 
Tom Lehrer, as a true artist of genius, required nothing but his recordings to distribute and sell his recordings.  It was all quite simple.  Dr. Lehrer was the first artist to self produce and publish.  Much to the annoyance of the record industry, he printed his own labels and paid for "vanity" pressings.  
Notice that his original maroon labels simply read, "Tom Lehrer Records".  This was in 1958, —waay before the web! And it all worked.  They are dull looking, but his pressing runs ran into the hundreds of thousands;  —probably millions.  He did this without radio play, advertising, reviews, or conventional promotion of any type.  All he did was perform a few night club engagements and he had acquired all the fame he required.  He did don't even need to show people what he looked like.  He broke every rule of commercial music sales, and it is probably a wonder that one of the major labels did not have him "bumped off".      

ALL the profit went to TOM LEHRER, and no one else.   

I own them all.  I was not wealthy  (a poor college student) and Dr. Lehrer  kept his prices lower than most records.  I was lucky enough to get to know Dr. Lehrer c. 1971 and see him perform living room benefit concerts for George McGovern's campaign. (I got in free as a drinks server).  Dr. Lehrer is one of the nicest guys I have ever met. That he made a lot of money from his performing and writing is one of the best stories I know.  Many people do not know that he started writing his songs when he was still in college (Harvard) and had become famous from playing at parties.  it was a small jump to being one of the highest paid night club performers of his time!  

He had NO management, NO publishing or recording contracts, NO promotion, NO sound gear, —nothing but his brain, vocal chords great piano hands and an uncanny ability to quickly write the funniest topical songs I have heard.  Oh yeah, he is one of the finest musicians I have known.

I was a professional musician in a popular combo while in College and for another 10 -11 years after college.  All of the horrible problems I experienced writing songs and performing with a pop band, were thoroughly unfamiliar to Dr. Lehrer.  Tom Lehrer is the ultimate success story of the adage, "Keep it SIMPLE".   It was nice to know that there was absolutely NO other person or company between Tom Lehrer as a songwriter and performer, and me as audience member, record buyer and Tom Lehrer FAN.  

This may never happen again, but if other artists would follow his example, I think your music dollar would go exclusively to the artist and the leaches that comprise the "music industry" would become extinct.  Artists would earn more money, but music would cost YOU less money!  Only the better artists would be well known. —Simple, eh? 

As for selling his records, I believe that he simply worked out a straight retail 20% profit margin and shipped records to record shops.  I have heard that his records sold out 100%, and did so FAST.  —I.e., Store returns were never an issue. I recall that he took a few years off from teaching to play the clubs and record albums. Lehrer needed only a piano and the simplest of professional recording gear and studio.  He was capable of starting and finishing a multi-gold selling album in an afternoon.  A second take?  I am not  sure this was ever needed...

He had NONE of the overhead that ALL other musical acts had.  He did not even need to purchase sound gear.  If a night club lacked a sound system, he simply booked himself elsewhere.  He was instantly in the top paying nightclubs from the beginning.  He became, almost instantly famous and in great demand for commercial  performances.  He avoided TV for a long time until 1965 and did a nation-wide network special.  No manager, no entourage, no security, no transportation...JUST HIM.  Why should any more be required? 

During those few years he did not teach Maths, the top night clubs fell over themselves to book Dr. Lehrer.  Tom Lehrer realised 100% of his profits. I wonder why other artists do not do this.  The web is a free advertising; —assuming you have the level of talent Dr. Lehrer has.  Tom Lehrer was paid as much or more than Mort Sahl (at his prime).  This is an incredible fact.  
It shows that if you have an exceptionally high quality product, you need NO "hype".  

SOO, after all these years, you can now LEGALLY POST ALL of Dr. Lehrer's catalogue without fear of having to pay a cent.  Tom Lehrer's recordings are owned by NO ONE, and you should NEVER have to purchase a Tom Lehrer recording.  People who try to sell his work are usually hustlers, and do so without any legal rights or permission from Dr. Lehrer.   A nominal charge for personal time, web servers, etc., is all that anyone should charge for his recordings.  But free sights like Archive.org, should make such a market pointless.  

ALL OF HIS RECORDINGS AND PUBLISHING ARE FREE.   It is ALL PUBLIC DOMAIN.  REALLY.  Dr. Lehrer has proven that ENOUGH is how much money anyone needs, and NOT a penny more.  Jesus will never need to kick over any tables as a result of Tom Lehrer's music career. 
   
Dr. Lehrer is alive, and 95 years old.  He believes that he has enough money (bless his soul).  He would rather see you post his recordings FOR FREE, and in FULL, than worry about paying him money that he does not need nor want. 

Sanity and Good Will are rare things.  

God Bless Dr. Lehrer.  
(My favourite Maths professor.)
